08:42.640 --> 08:45.623
ecology. Do you think we can safely experiment, as 
a matter of fact, with modifying the climate on the

08:46.564 --> 08:52.170
Earth? Well, we're doing it. We can't do the 
paperwork, though. You were going to come back and

08:55.637 --> 08:57.580
report to me. Oh, I forgot. I was wondering if you'd 
like a little snack for lunch. It's getting on

09:03.468 --> 09:05.751
toward that time. I don't have any honey, and I 
don't have any avocado to make you a honey avocado.

09:10.837 --> 09:12.940
Let me move your coffee pot over here. Yes, I would 
very much. Thank you. I think we can wind this thing

09:15.664 --> 09:19.609
up for you in a few minutes here.

09:23.470 --> 09:24.612
What was your question again? I was talking about 
modifying it twice or three times in our

09:24.632 --> 09:27.998
conversation. Something's come up with the idea 
of the ecology system and modifying the climate.

09:33.748 --> 09:35.010
We are modifying it. We probably are modifying the 
climate. That is almost certain. By adding carbon

09:39.739 --> 09:45.509
dioxide to

09:39.739 --> 09:45.509
the atmosphere. And we're adding a lot. We're 
adding now. About a half of 1% of the, every year,

09:49.087 --> 09:59.660
we're adding a half of 1% of the atmospheric carbon 
dioxide to the atmosphere.

09:59.680 --> 10:00.220
We're pretty close to that. And this is something 
that we don't want to do. We're just doing it by

10:03.705 --> 10:05.807
burning fossil fuels. And the real question is, 
what's going to happen? It's a great geophysical

10:09.952 --> 10:12.596
experiment in one way. It's also maybe a great 
concern to human beings. Now, the ocean enters

10:18.196 --> 10:20.699
into this in a profound way. We're actually 
burning fossil fuels about carbon dioxide

10:22.502 --> 10:42.668
production is about 1% of the atmospheric carbon 
dioxide every year,

10:22.502 --> 10:42.668
going up to 3% or 4% maybe in 100 years if we keep on 
burning coal.

10:47.002 --> 10:49.926
But about half of this at the present time goes into 
the ocean. What do you think? An unknown

10:54.832 --> 11:03.964
proportion goes into the biosphere, and maybe not 
any goes into the biosphere, but maybe a

10:54.832 --> 11:03.964
significant amount.

11:03.984 --> 11:08.911
The land biosphere,

11:03.984 --> 11:08.911
I think. The reason that we're able to absorb half 
of it in the ocean is that the ocean has something

11:08.931 --> 11:15.439
called a bucker mechanism of seawater. That is, 
there are carbonate ions in the ocean which have

11:16.330 --> 11:26.865
two negative charges that can be turned into 
bicarbonate if you add CO2. Bicarbonate has only

11:28.106 --> 11:32.693
one negative charge.

11:32.713 --> 11:43.688
As long as the carbonate ion is present,

11:32.713 --> 11:43.688
the ocean can absorb CO2 by transforming the 
carbonate into bicarbonate. However, it looks as

11:44.984 --> 11:55.921
if, as time goes on, we're going to use up the 
carbonate ion in the ocean, and therefore the

11:44.984 --> 11:55.921
ocean won't be able to absorb very much CO2. Most of 
it will stay in the atmosphere. So that will make

11:58.946 --> 12:04.795
the situation worse than it is

11:58.946 --> 12:04.795
now. Moreover, if we do this, we're going to heat up 
the surface waters of the ocean because the

12:04.815 --> 12:13.388
atmosphere will get warm again. And they won't be 
able to hold so much carbonic acid gas. So more

12:19.024 --> 12:27.273
carbon dioxide will get into the air from the 
ocean,

12:19.024 --> 12:27.273
because the ocean will be losing it. Moreover,

12:27.293 --> 12:40.287
as the atmosphere heats up and as the ocean surface 
layer heats up, there will be more evaporation and

12:27.293 --> 12:40.287
more cloud formation. This may be a 
countervailing effect. Nobody really knows what

12:43.015 --> 13:07.980
the effect will be, whether it will increase the 
albedo of the earth, that is, the reflectivity, so

12:43.015 --> 13:07.980
we get less incoming radiation, or whether it 
will, in fact, increase the temperature in order

12:43.015 --> 13:07.980
to get, because clouds radiate infrared at a lower 
temperature than the ground surface does, you may

12:43.015 --> 13:07.980
therefore have to raise the temperature in order 
to get enough radiation out to maintain a heat

12:43.015 --> 13:07.980
balance. I'm quite uncertain what's going to 
happen. All the climatic models

13:11.350 --> 13:18.881
are fatally weak because they're unable to model 
the ocean. And they're unable to modify the cloud

13:21.464 --> 13:25.570
formation of the ocean. You have to learn how to do 
this. And this will be, I think, a combination of

13:28.013 --> 13:32.259
observation and theory. It can't be done by either 
one alone. You observe cloud formation over the

13:35.524 --> 13:37.847
ocean. You observe the albedo of the clouds and 
their infrared radiation and see what happens in

13:38.705 --> 13:49.798
different areas under the variations we now get. 
And from this, develop a better theory of cloud

13:50.499 --> 13:56.526
formation and a better theory of the interaction 
between the sea and the air.

14:00.070 --> 14:05.016
One thing that's characteristic of the ocean is 
that it carries about half the heat. from low

14:06.110 --> 14:07.651
latitudes to high latitudes. The other half is 
carried in the air. Nobody knows whether it's 40%

14:11.795 --> 14:14.377
or 50% or 60%. That makes a lot of difference in 
models, not in space models. Present

14:19.321 --> 14:24.266
climatological models assume one of two things 
about the ocean. Either that the ocean is a swamp

14:24.326 --> 14:35.155
from which water can evaporate but no heat can be 
absorbed because it's such a thin layer of water,

14:24.326 --> 14:35.155
or that it's got an infinite heat capacity. 
Neither of which is true. The truth is somewhere in

14:38.042 --> 14:41.146
between. And the models just can't take account of 
that. I don't think you're going to be able to get

14:49.797 --> 14:56.526
very much further to it unless you have a lot more 
studies of the interaction between the sea and the

14:49.797 --> 14:56.526
air. Rather than talk about climate 
modification, I'd like to talk about climate and

14:58.208 --> 15:04.956
what's going to happen to it. And the only thing we 
can say with any certainty now about climate is

15:05.662 --> 15:13.093
that the climate fluctuates. Sometimes it's one 
way, and sometimes it's another. And we know that

15:18.160 --> 15:20.003
it always has fluctuated. The longer the period of 
observation, the greater the fluctuation.

15:23.608 --> 15:28.795
That's characteristic of what are called 
stochastic processes. And it's very likely that

15:28.815 --> 15:32.040
the climate's going to get worse. It's no more 
likely that the climate will get better, but it's

15:33.202 --> 15:37.949
equally likely that it will get worse. It's going 
to vary somehow. And we have to be prudent and to act

15:41.133 --> 15:47.703
as if we're going to get worse, even though it may 
not.

15:50.527 --> 15:52.810
That means we have to do a lot of things about 
agriculture. But in order to know what to do about

15:53.591 --> 15:57.577
agriculture, we have to know what's going to 
happen. If the climate does get worse, what does

15:58.318 --> 16:01.082
that mean? Horse latitudes shift north or south. 
Does it mean you get more or less precipitation?

16:06.729 --> 16:09.233
Does it mean the pattern of precipitation 
changes? Does it mean that the temperature

16:09.673 --> 16:12.297
patterns change? And if so, in what way are they 
going to change? Climatology at the present time

16:15.642 --> 16:20.608
is a very primitive science. And half of 
climatology is oceanography. But the Global

16:24.394 --> 16:31.103
Atmospheric Research Program, which involves 
oceanography as well as meteorology, that it's

16:31.792 --> 16:43.242
just a very important thing to be doing from a 
purely practical point of view, let alone from a

16:31.792 --> 16:43.242
theoretical and scientifically interesting 
point of view. But, you know, the notion that you

16:43.262 --> 16:55.793
dam up the Bering Sea or run the Amur River into the 
Arctic or something like that, these are all

16:43.262 --> 16:55.793
trivial problems compared to the real problem. 
What's going to happen to the climate without our

16:55.813 --> 16:58.336
doing a goddamn thing? Except putting CO2 into it. 
on a very large scale? Do we have to abandon carbon

17:02.924 --> 17:07.529
dioxide in production? Do we have to abandon the 
use of fossil fuels because we're going to change

17:07.689 --> 17:13.835
the climate so drastically by continuing to use 
them? Or can we continue to use them and prepare for

17:15.056 --> 17:19.501
what changes will occur?

