The one thing that strikes me as consistent in your 
career, if I may use that word, or consistently

17:29.723 --> 17:38.213
apparent in your career, is the scientist as 
public man. Do you have any particular

17:39.214 --> 17:48.706
philosophical views about what the scientist's 
responsibility is to the public? Well,

17:48.726 --> 17:52.631
personally, he has the same responsibility as 
everybody else. He's a good citizen. But he also

17:55.795 --> 17:57.857
has special responsibilities.

18:03.406 --> 18:19.470
because he either knows something that other 
people don't know, or because he has ways of

18:03.406 --> 18:19.470
finding out things that other people don't know 
about.

18:19.490 --> 18:26.120
And I think that the scientist has maybe two 
responsibilities. One is to be an entertainer, to

18:26.400 --> 18:33.210
be, like other artists, give people pleasure and 
happiness. And this is particularly obvious with

18:37.125 --> 18:39.307
astronomy. People really are fascinated by 
astronomy.

18:46.033 --> 18:51.238
And it has some very deep meaning to people, which 
is hard to describe. But you can see it when you look

18:51.298 --> 18:58.845
at an audience being talked to by an astronomer or 
by somebody who talks about astronomy. They often

18:59.705 --> 19:01.527
have tears in their eyes. overwhelmingly 
emotionally involved in it. And that's the

19:05.784 --> 19:09.349
entertainment aspect of science. Seafloor 
spreading, plate tectonics,

19:09.369 --> 19:28.020
whether there's light on Mars, what's the history 
of the Earth, what's the history of living

19:09.369 --> 19:28.020
creatures, what's the diversity of living 
creatures, all their peculiar and funny ways and

19:09.369 --> 19:28.020
interesting ways.

19:29.755 --> 19:36.305
Let's leave that tentative curtain that we see out 
there in front of us. These are all kind of things

19:36.325 --> 19:42.315
that Cousteau does and that many people do. These 
are very important aspects of the scientist's

19:42.355 --> 19:47.262
responsibility to the public. After all, the 
public's paying for what he does. They ought to get

19:49.185 --> 19:50.247
something out of it. The other thing, of course, is 
that the scientist has

19:59.253 --> 20:17.277
the responsibility of laying the basis for a 
humane technology, a technology which serves the

19:59.253 --> 20:17.277
interests of people and doesn't disserve the 
interests of people. The technologists

20:17.297 --> 20:26.610
themselves have a major responsibility here, but 
most modern technology is based on science,

20:27.400 --> 20:44.222
knowledge of nature and knowledge of ourselves 
and knowledge of other living creatures,

20:27.400 --> 20:44.222
biological knowledge, scientific knowledge of 
living things and of the inanimate world. So I

20:44.242 --> 20:54.235
think

20:44.242 --> 20:54.235
one of the responsibilities of the scientists was 
to try

20:44.242 --> 20:54.235
to consider and talk about and think about, or to 
consider, think about, and talk about, put them in

20:55.531 --> 21:12.996
that order, what are the likely consequences of 
increasing, of increases in scientific

20:55.531 --> 21:12.996
knowledge?

21:14.718 --> 21:25.453
And to do that in such a way that you don't scare 
people, but you

21:14.718 --> 21:25.453
give them a chance to make intelligent choices and 
intelligent decisions. You can't make the

21:25.923 --> 21:31.910
decisions for them, but you can give them the 
knowledge by which they can make better

21:25.923 --> 21:31.910
decisions.

21:34.774 --> 21:36.816
And then the final thing is to do good science. 
That's a responsibility, too, because science is

21:36.876 --> 21:52.555
a human activity of,

21:36.876 --> 21:52.555
how to put it, Science is something that people can 
do. Finding out about the world and about

21:58.186 --> 22:06.014
ourselves is an important human activity, 
something that makes people human. It gives them a

22:06.995 --> 22:16.104
higher humanity and a more intense

22:06.995 --> 22:16.104
experience. Most scientists,

22:18.467 --> 22:23.892
of course, feel this very strongly. I think 
they're right

22:24.597 --> 22:37.637
that it's one of the wonderful things about human 
beings that they can understand nature, up to a

22:24.597 --> 22:37.637
point at least. And we haven't reached that limit 
yet. I don't want to just put you ahead as fast as we

22:39.900 --> 22:46.210
can to find out as much as we can. Maybe we will find 
eventually one of two things will happen, that

22:46.230 --> 22:53.541
science becomes so complicated If it loses its 
unity and its integrity, therefore people won't

22:54.719 --> 23:02.288
be interested in it. No, it's not necessary. I 
mean, it's quite possible that we could develop a

23:02.888 --> 23:10.277
civilization that couldn't care less about 
knowing about nature. Alternatively, the

23:10.297 --> 23:22.971
possibility is it will come up against barriers in 
our minds or limitations of our own minds and our

23:10.297 --> 23:22.971
own ability to understand. That isn't in sight 
yet, but it may be within the next 100 years. I guess

23:31.794 --> 23:37.163
that science is, you can think of science sort of 
like you think about population. It can't go on

23:37.203 --> 23:38.385
forever. The rate at which we're learning things 
is accelerating. That leads to a discontinuity of

23:43.733 --> 23:49.823
something. An exponential curve is by 
fundamentally an unstable, leads to a

23:54.541 --> 24:01.187
discontinuity.

24:04.230 --> 24:07.353
So it can't go on exponentially. In other words, 
maybe we'll go like this and level off like that.

24:10.576 --> 24:17.563
Maybe we'll go like this and go like

24:10.576 --> 24:17.563
that. One of those two things might happen. Now, I 
have one final question, and you're long

24:32.020 --> 24:38.809
